primarily affects the inner ear?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Otitis externa","Otitis media","Labyrinthitis","Cerumen impaction","Eustachian tube dysfunction"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELabyrinthitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammatory condition of the inner ear labyrinth, affecting both the vestibular and cochlear portions. This presents with vertigo, hearing loss, and balance disturbance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOtitis externa\u003C/strong\u003E is an infection of the external ear canal, whilst \u003Cstrong\u003Eotitis media\u003C/strong\u003E is inflammation or infection of the middle ear space. \u003Cstrong\u003ECerumen impaction\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in the external ear canal, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eeustachian tube dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E affects the tube connecting the middle ear to the nasopharynx. The inner ear contains delicate structures including the semicircular canals for balance, and the cochlea for hearing. Inflammation of these structures in labyrinthitis can significantly impact both balance and hearing function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Labyrinthitis is an inflammatory condition affecting the inner ear labyrinth, which contains both the vestibular and cochlear components.","Inner ear structures include the semicircular canals, vestibule, and cochlea, which are responsible for balance and hearing.","Common inner ear conditions include labyrinthitis, benign paroxysmal positional vertigo, and M\u00e9ni\u00e8re disease."],"references":["Bae CH, Na HG, Choi YS. Current diagnosis and treatment of vestibular neuritis: a narrative review. J Yeungnam Med Sci. 2022 Apr;39(2):81-88. doi: 10.12701/yujm.2021.01228. Epub 2021 Aug 9. PMID: 34411472; PMCID: PMC8913909.","Oussoren FK, Schermer TR, Bruintjes TD, Leeuwen RBV. Idiopathic Labyrinthitis: Symptoms, Clinical Characteristics, and Prognosis. J Int Adv Otol. 2023 